post_text:
Good Evening Southland Family,

As we embark on this new journey called Remote Learning, we are relying on technology more than ever. To assist parents and students, a video will air on the Matteson School District 162 YouTube channel tonight at 7:00 PM. This video will cover key points that will help you with the use of technology rolled out by the district in the most effective, efficient and productive manner. If you have any technology-related questions, they can be asked in the live chat that will be available on the YouTube page for this video. District technology administrators will be answering your questions in real-time. Thank you and we look forward to achieving continued excellence in education. Through technology, the possibilities truly are unlimited.

Link to video: https://youtu.be/zQEjJnGnWrg

post_text:
As they prepare to head off to the next chapter in their educational journey, Southland is still celebrating the historic Class of 2020. The 136-member Class of 2020 earned a record $60 million in merit-based scholarships to scores of colleges and universities across the country. In addition, several members of the class were awarded national, local, state, regional and other scholarships.

Today, we celebrate our scholarship winners.

Congratulations to our 2020 national scholarship winners:
Kailah Hester, Questbridge National College Match Scholarship

Ashley Meeky, National Football League Players Association Scholarship

Malik Fountain, Blacks at Microsoft Scholarship

Know a member of Southland's Class of 2020 awarded a scholarship? Please let us know and keep us updated on all of the great news about our newest alumni.
#SouthlandProud #Classof2020

post_text:
We are proud of the accomplishments of one of our feeder districts, Matteson School District 162. The time for the 162 Class of 2020 Virtual Commencement Ceremony is almost upon us! We are all proud of the perseverance, determination and grit that the graduates demonstrated in order to achieve academic excellence despite the challenges that they faced due to COVID-19. There will be a total of 289 graduates. 177 of these students have maintained a 3.0 grade point average or higher. In addition to that, District 162 has 19 valedictorians with a 4.67 grade point average. Truly remarkable!

The Class of 2020 comes together one final time when the commencement ceremony streams tomorrow, June 27th at 4 PM. Click the link to view a video from some of the District 162 administrators. Stay safe. Stay connected.

Southland trivia:
This co-valedictorian of the Class of 2019 was also Southland's first Gates Millennium scholar.
Answer: Maia Boyd. Maia not only received Southland's first Gates Millennium Scholarship, she was also a Questbridge National College Match Scholarship winner. Maia chose to attend the University of Chicago. Her fellow valedictorian was Armanti Reed who chose to attend Yale University.

She was Southland's first female drum major.
Answer: Olivia Brown, Class of 2019, achieved her goal of becoming Southland's first female drum major. In 2019-2020, the band was led by three female drum majors.

post_text:
She was "the voice of Southland."

Andrea Kidd (1956-2018). Every graduation from 2014 to 2017, Mrs. Kidd was the mistress of ceremonies for Southland commencement ceremonies. Mrs. Kidd wore many hats at Southland. Mrs. Kidd served Southland as the Director of Operations, Director of Special Education and the Director of Alumni Relations.

Her contributions will never be forgotten. She made sure that Southland was for all students. Mrs. Kidd loved "the children" and we love her and miss her. Click on the link to view the tribute to Mrs. Kidd that was played during the 2019 commencement. #SevenDaysofSouthland

Southland salutes the Class of 2019. Their class spirit was unmatched. They were a class of firsts and achievements that some thought would be hard to surpass.

Members of this class earned almost perfect SAT scores. They earned an amazing $54 million in merit-based scholarships. Keita Allen was the first Southland admission to MIT. Performance in the Round won their third straight state championship, a feat never accomplished before in state history. The Class of 2019 left a mark not soon to be forgotten.

Class of 2019, we are #SouthlandProud of you. #SevenDaysofSouthland

post_text:
"It's senior season!" That was the shout heard in the hallways of Southland last spring. Today we celebrate the Class of 2019! The Class of 2019 commencement ceremony will air on our Youtube channel at 4 p.m. today.

The Class of 2019 was another "class of firsts." Southland's first Gates Millennium Scholar. Southland's first admission to MIT. The first female drum major.

Just like the many classes before them, the Class of 2019 knew what they needed to do to break all of the school's records. And they did just that in an extraordinary fashion, earning an astonishing $54.2 million in merit-based scholarships. They were competitive in the classroom, on the court and even on the stage. They knew what they wanted and they went out to get it. They did the one thing eagles do best, fly! #SevenDaysofSouthland

Southland trivia:
This co-valedictorian of the Class of 2019 was also Southland's first Gates Millennium scholar.

She was Southland's first female drum major.

post_text:
Southland trivia:
Southland's Group Interpretation won a state championship based on this Academy Award nominated movie and book of the same title.

Answer: Hidden Figures

2017 was a golden year for the drama and forensics team. Not only did Southland's Group Interpretation ensemble's Hidden Figures performance take first at the IHSA State Tournament, but so did Southland's Performance in the Round Team with their performance of Anansi the Spider.

Southland's Hidden Figures journey began when Coordinator of Dance Gloria Chatman was inspired by the movie to choreograph dances for the Black History program. Class of 2018 dance member Michael Jones casually mentioned that Katherine Johnson, the NASA mathematician who Taraji P. Henson played in the movie, was his great aunt. The rest is Southland history! #SevenDaysofSouthland

post_text:
Southland Class of 2020 is proud to present the SENIOR SHOWCASE!

Today, we showcase and celebrate
MS. GIA FOX!

Gia Fox is a happy, positive young woman who sees her destiny following in the path of healthcare. Specifically, she sees herself becoming a Neonatal Intensive Care Unit Nurse (NICU) because of how much she adores newborn babies. She knows that she will have to work hard to become a registered nurse, but she's up for the challenge.

Her favorite memory will always be when she stepped out onto the court for her last home game on her beloved Southland Volleyball Team. But NO ONE will forget that Gia Fox may likely be the biggest JUICE WRLD fan on Planet Earth.

She's been dreaming of enrolling in a college in Florida where many of her family currently resides. While COVID-19 may have affected her plans, she has finally decided to move forward with her dreams of taking her talents to Florida.

She has decided...and it's
MIAMI DADE COLLEGE!

We wish Gia all the best in sunny Florida!!!!
Congratulations Gia & The Class of 2020!

#Classof2020 #SouthlandProud

The Southland SENIOR SHOWCASE continues!

Today, we showcase and celebrate
MS. TAYLOR ADAMS!

Taylor has been accepted to 17 colleges and universities!

She plans on majoring in political science to pursue a career in law, specifically as a criminal defense attorney. Equality is so important to her; she believes we need more black lawyers in order to create opportunities for the voices of African Americans to be heard and represented.

Her favorite Southland memory? Sophomore year performing a tap dance along with several other southland dancers live on WCIU “The U” (Which can be viewed by clicking the link: https://youtu.be/255x3cK7OnY?t=404). Ms. Adams is looking forward to joining student organizations on campus such as the NAACP. She wants to meet new people and take fascinating new courses.

While she had a multitude of options--it's OFFICIAL---Taylor will be attending

The University of Louisville!!!

Go Cardinals!!
Congratulations Taylor & The Class of 2020!

#Classof2020 #SouthlandProud

An update: Gloria Chatman, Southland's coordinator of dance, received a special gift from her Southland dancers this week. Mrs. Chatman's husband, Demetrius, has been hospitalized and fighting the COVID-19 virus. The response to the Chatman family's request for donors who have survived the virus to donate blood was overwhelming and her husband received the convalescent plasma treatment from blood donations and is improving!

Mrs. Chatman appeared in a story by NBC Chicago about the new treatment and will be on V103 Chicago this morning at around 7:30 a.m. with Darryl Dennard sharing her family's journey.

Enjoy our 2017 state champion Group Interpretation performance of "Hidden Figures."

In 2017 the Southland campus was transformed by the story of "Hidden Figures." One of the members of our Southland family, Michael Jones (Class of 2018) was the great nephew of Katherine Johnson, the trailblazing NASA mathematician who was portrayed by Taraji P. Henson in the movie.

The entire school viewed the movie together. Students wrote letters to Mrs. Johnson that were delivered to her. Our speech team produced this wonderful Group Interpretation piece that won the state championship!

Mrs. Johnson passed away on February 24th of this year. We honor her legacy and excellence.

Juniors Nyah Ware and Bri'Yon Watts will compete in the August Wilson Monologue Competition Chicago Regional Finals on Monday, March 9 at the Goodman Theatre at 6 p.m. in Chicago. Come out and support our Eagles!

The first and second place winners will receive an all-expense paid trip to New York to compete in the National Finals at the August Wilson Theatre on Broadway.

Open to Chicago area high school sophomores, juniors, and seniors, the competition gives students an opportunity to explore and share the richness of August Wilson’s Century Cycle. Students are asked to prepare and perform a 2-3 minute monologue of their choosing from one of the ten plays in August Wilson’s Century Cycle.

In 2013, Morgan Brown, Class of 2014, took first place in the Chicago competition and went on to compete in the finals in New York City.

Good luck to Nyah and Bri'Yon! Your Southland Family is cheering you on!

Ms. Grutzius’ senior English class just completed a weeklong guest speaker series to celebrate Black History Month.

Students selected an influential, local community member as part of the “Someone You Should Know” series. Guests were Chicago Sun-Times columnist and professor John W. Fountain, Cook County Commissioner Donna Miller, former University Village mayor Vivian Covington, Appellate Judge Cynthia Cobbs, CEO, life coach and speaker Najm Ali who is the 2019/2020 Ms. American Elegance Woman and our own Dr. Corey Levy.

Our special guests discussed finding one’s purpose, overcoming obstacles and fears, networking, giving back to the community and stories of inspiration about creating a path to success and personal fulfillment.

The seniors want to thank all of our special guests for sharing time and valuable life lessons. #BlackHistory #BlackExcellence

post_text:
The Southland Family extends its condolences to the family of NASA pioneer, Katherine Johnson, the great aunt of Southland alumni Michael Jones Jr. who passed away today. Mrs. Johnson, a NASA mathematician, was 101.

Johnson "was an American hero and her pioneering legacy will never be forgotten," NASA administrator Jim Bridenstine wrote on Twitter today.

Johnson was portrayed by Taraji P. Henson in the Oscar-nominated 2016 film "Hidden Figures" about trailblazing women whose work at NASA was integral during the Space Race.

In February 2017, Southland celebrated Mrs. Johnson during our Black History program and throughout our curriculum. The entire school screened the movie "Hidden Figures." Students studied the time period and the speech team won state in Group Interpretation for their performance of "Hidden Figures." Students wrote letters to Mrs. Johnson and a photo book of all the activities surrounding "Hidden Figures" was delivered to Mrs. Johnson by her great nephew Michael, Class of 2018.

Rest in Peace, Mrs. Johnson. We celebrate and honor your legacy of excellence.

All Girls Matter. Last week a group of Southland students participated in the All Girls Matter Empowerment Expo hosted by America’s Big Sisters Foundation . The foundation which was founded by Tragil Wade, the big sister of NBA Star Dwyane Wade, seeks to empower, encourage and educate young ladies.

post_text:
Congratulations to Southland's Speech team which placed third in the regional tournament held at Marian Catholic last Saturday. Southland placed first in four of fourteen individual events, scored second in one event and placed third and fourth in each of three events.

Southland also placed second in the "Performance in the Round" category, presenting an excerpt from "for colored girls who have considered suicide/when the rainbow is enuf," a dramatic prose poem.

Southland's first place medalists in individual competitions were: Josh Tisdale for Humorous Interpretation; Nyah Ware for Impromptu Speaking; Bri'Yon Watts for Poetry Reading and Savannah Taffe in Radio Speaking.

Sectionals will be this Saturday at Reavis High School in Burbank. Keep soaring Eagles. We are #SouthlandProud of you!

post_text: The annual HBCU Band Recruitment Night hosted by Southland College Prep will be held at 5 p.m. today. Last year representatives of more than 20 Historically Black Colleges and University bands heard auditions performed by scores of band students from South Cook and Will County area high schools and offered scholarships on the spot. This year 22 HBCUs are scheduled to attend including Florida A & M, University of Arkansas at Pine Bluff, Hampton University, Howard University, and Morehouse College.

post_text:
Congratulations to senior Niyela Garza! Niyela was named one of four Outstanding Charter School Seniors by the Illinois Network of Charter Schools today at a surprise rally. Niyela received a check for $1,000 from INCS. Niyela is secretary of Southland’s National Honor Society chapter and an active member of Southland’s Interact Community Services and Teens Helping Teens groups.

She has been accepted by the University of Missouri, Eastern Illinois University, University of Houston and Xavier University of Louisiana where she has been offered a full tuition and expenses scholarship.

Keep soaring Niyela! We are #SouthlandProud of you!

post_text:
Congratulations to Kailah Hester! Kailah is the recipient of the Questbridge Scholarship. She has earned a full, four-year scholarship to Dartmouth, one of America's elite Ivy League institutions. Kailah, we are #SouthlandProud of you!

Out of 14,926 applicants, QuestBridge selected 5,842 Finalists who were considered for the QuestBridge National College Match Scholarship. Of these Finalists, 1,127 outstanding students were selected as this year’s Match Scholarship Recipients. This is the highest number of Match Scholarship Recipients to-date for QuestBridge. Kailah's scholarship is valued at over $300,000.
